>>45359441
I've had this discussion before. More than once. In summary:

>Fallout has established mutants exist
>they have to reproduce or
> the new races wouldn't express genetically

The discussion isn't about "IF mutants" now, it's about "which mutants."
>given Earth biosphere
>which animals are genetically hardy enough
>which environments would be most conducive toward survival
>what factors generate stable mutations
>which ones are sentient?
>which ones are sapient?

I don't even like rats, but they're almost a given. Their genetics are fairly amazing in the animal kingdom, they live everywhere as a hundred different species, so some enclave somewhere is in the right location.

Mutations are almost certainly the result of radiation plus biological warfare plus (perhaps) medical viruses &/or vaccines to counteract biowarfare and other diseases. Escaped labrats in bombed cities living in every imaginable urban and semi-urban environment, interbreeding with other rat/mouse species.

What other animals have similar opportunity and adaptability? Other lab animals (cats dogs rabbits). As civilization collapsed, very desperate attempts would be common.

Which wild animals? Bats. Raccoons maybe, they are indigenous worldwide in several species. Lemurs & primates already did this once, under less harsh conditions. But, still.

I always advocate for ocean life, especially cephalopods. Some are highly intelligent, widespread, highly adaptable, ancient beyond imagination, occupy extremely broad environments exposed to many concentrations and combinations of mutagenics.

Fallout should have a hundred new semi- and fully sapient mutant species. Some may just be emerging, but humans are no longer alone. Remember, include genetically engineered species for war, like Tank Girl 'roos.

Quoted By: >>45374217
>>45373449
Having written multiple pieces that broke the 100k mark, here's some good long-term advice.
Learn to write both by pantsing and planning. It's always better if you have some idea what you want to say that day, but if it's only two words on a scrap of paper then you need to have the balls to follow that wherever it leads.
Write down every fucking dumb idea. You never know where they'll slot in.
Think about your characters in your idle moments. Don't obsess, but use your idle moments to consider how they might have done something recent differently than you. It sounds silly, but brainstorming like this will help you understand their setting.
Even the experienced guys have doubts about their ideas. Learn to find the thread in your story that drives you. Hold the fuck onto it. I've had ideas that took over a year to go from idea to final draft. I knew when to shift onto other projects; coming back to one is rarely a wellspring of motivation. Usually, it's just me looking at what I have and seeing the missing piece.

Put yourself into something and it will pay off.

Remember the Backrooms meme?
People have started turning it into a collection of unsettling stories similar to the SCP Foundation, where each “level” is a different environment. They created in-universe organizations and groups, which I think is kinda dumb and unnecessary, but the entries themselves are pretty cool. I’m mentioning this because SCP isn’t really open to waifurs, and this may be an opportunity to shill waifurs before whatever this becomes gets popular (or dies). There’s likely not a whole lot of expectations required to write a Backrooms entry like there is with new SCPs, so if you’re interested, hop on while the opportunity is open.
